<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Maclaurin Series</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Calculus/MaclaurinSeries=
.nb" download=3D"MaclaurinSeries.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.=
com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" a=
lt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
A Maclaurin series is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TaylorSeri=
es.html">Taylor series</a> expansion
of a function about 0,
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/MaclaurinSeries/NumberedEquation1.svg" data-src-small=3D"/ima=
ges/equations/MaclaurinSeries/NumberedEquation1_400.svg" data-src-default=
=3D"/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numbe=
redequation swappable" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" width=3D"47=
7" data-big=3D"477 42" data-small=3D"273 89" border=3D"0" alt=3D" f(x)=3Df(=
0)+f^'(0)x+(f^('')(0))/(2!)x^2+(f^((3))(0))/(3!)x^3+...+(f^((n))(0))/(n!)x^=
n+.... " height=3D"42"></td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
Maclaurin series are named after the Scottish mathematician Colin Maclaurin=
.
</p>
<p>
The Maclaurin series of a function <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.co=
m/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" sty=
le=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"2=
1" alt=3D"f(x)"> up to order <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/imag=
es/equations/MaclaurinSeries/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"n"> may be found using <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/lang=
uage/ref/Series.html">Series</a></tt>[<i>f</i>,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries=
/Inline3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D"21" alt=3D"{"><i>x</i>, 0, <i>n</i><=
img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries/I=
nline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%=
" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D"21" alt=3D"}">]. The <img src=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries/Inline5.svg" clas=
s=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" w=
idth=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n">th term of a Maclaurin series of a funct=
ion <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSer=
ies/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"12" height=3D"21" alt=3D"f"> can be computed i=
n the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram.com/language/">Wolfram
 Language</a> using <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wolfram.com/language/re=
f/SeriesCoefficient.html">SeriesCoefficient</a></tt>[<i>f</i>,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries=
/Inline7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D"21" alt=3D"{"><i>x</i>, 0, <i>n</i><=
img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/MaclaurinSeries/I=
nline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%=
" border=3D"0" width=3D"6" height=3D"21" alt=3D"}">] and is given by the in=
verse <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Z-Transform.html">Z-transfor=
m</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/MaclaurinSeries/NumberedEquation2.svg" class=3D"numberedequat=
ion" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"147" he=
ight=3D"40" alt=3D" a_n=3DZ^(-1)[f(1/x)](n). "></td><td align=3D"right" wid=
th=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn2" class=3D"eqnum">
(2)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
Maclaurin series are a type of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Ser=
iesExpansion.html">series expansion</a> in which all terms are nonnegative =
integer powers of the variable. Other more general
 types of series include the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Laure=
ntSeries.html">Laurent series</a> and
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PuiseuxSeries.html">Puiseux s=
eries</a>.
</p>
<p>
Maclaurin series for common functions include=20
</p>
